more than 1 billion children in the world have been trampled on by poverty
the annual report published by the united nations children 's fund ( unicef ) today pointed out that more than 1 billion children in the world are suffering from poverty , war , and the outbreak of aids .
the united nations children 's fund ( unicef ) said that children under the covenant on children 's rights in 1989 have the right to have a healthy and stable environment for growth , and some of the reasons are that the governments of various countries have failed to carry out human rights and economic reforms .
" when half of the world 's children grow in hunger and unhealthy environment , we have become the target of attacks and the entire village of the whole world , " said the president of the un children 's fund 's executive committee , ms christine fang , in london .
" the governments of many countries are making a deliberate choice that will actually hurt children , " berri added .
the united nations children 's fund ( unicef ) and the research personnel of the london economic institute and the university of britons have jointly compiled statistics to expose the terror of children in most parts of the world .
researchers found that about 640 million children in the world were unable to get safe drinking water , 260 million children could not enjoy health services , and 140 million children ( most girls ) had never been able to learn .
researchers pointed out that even more serious is that at least 700 million children are suffering from various forms of " serious exploitation " , including the failure to contact information and enjoy public health facilities .
the united nations children 's fund ( unicef ) today published its 10 th annual report , pointing out that war and aids have destroyed various networks that are usually able to protect children , and children have become direct victims of war and aids .
china puts pressure on eu to lift arms embargo
the european union ( eu ) today rejected the pressure from chinese premier wen jiabao , hoping to end the arms embargo on china as soon as possible , but also said it would strive to lift the 15 - year - old embargo .
the statement was made by the netherlands , the rotating eu president , after the china - eu summit .
the netherlands said that it was not necessary to speculate on how the eu could stop the ban on the embargo .
the european union imposed an arms embargo on beijing after the 1989 tiananmen square massacre .
although the arms embargo issue has been cast over the shadow of the china - eu summit , the two sides still signed some trade and other agreements at the meeting .
china and the eu both claimed that these agreements have strengthened their " strategic partnership . "
in a joint statement issued after the summit meeting with chinese premier wen jiabao , the eu said : " the eu side has confirmed its political wish to continue to lift the embargo . "
the statement pointed out that the chinese delegation " welcomes this positive message and believes that this message is beneficial to the healthy development of china 's extensive strategic partnership with the eu . "
at the news conference after the summit , wen jiabao did not hide his bad , saying that the embargo " failed to reflect the partnership between china and the eu . "
wen jiabao said : " this embargo is the result of the cold war , and it cannot reflect the current situation , and still less does it reflect the partnership between china and the eu . "
under the leadership of france , some eu countries have pushed the lifting of the arms embargo , claiming that the ban is already outdated .
under the circumstances of not expanding the relevant laws of the eu , people of insight in the eu are worried that the lifting of the embargo may open up the flood control gate for arms sales , and this has encouraged china 's military strength .
" i explained the eu has the intention to lift the embargo , but i also pointed out that the lifting of the ban and the adjustment of the criteria for arms exports are related to each other , " said dutch prime minister barkefsky .
