( international ) united nations warns against increase in global drug abuse in 2005
xinhua news agency , vienna , december 17 ( reporter song guocheng ) - the united nations office for drug control and crime prevention warned in a press release on the 17 th that due to the increase in the output of heroin in afghanistan , the world 's black market is expected to be stable , and the prices of heroin are increasing , thus causing more deaths .
he also warned officials from the health and anti - drug organizations in europe and the neighboring countries that they are concerned about the latest trend of drug - planting and international drug - related crimes in afghanistan .
according to statistics provided by the united nations office for drug control and crime prevention in vienna , the amount of heroin in afghanistan dropped by 94% in 2001 , and the amount of heroin in the european black market decreased by 50 percent in the second year .
from 2000 to 2002 , the number of drug addicts in europe dropped by 20 percent .
he said that compared with 2003 , the area of opium cultivation in afghanistan has increased by 64% , and the output of heroin has reached over 500 tons , which is higher than the volume of the global heroin black market , which means that the global level of drug abuse and the number of drug deaths have increased accordingly .
he said that the sources of narcotics in afghanistan have already constituted a " clear and practical threat " to the global anti - drug efforts , and the increase in the supply of heroin on the black market means the " death sentence " for drug addicts .
according to estimates , the number of deaths caused by excessive drug abuse every year in the world is about 100,000 .
